Title : Nicholas Brooks
Text : {{other people}}
'''Nicholas Peter Brooks''', [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]] (14 January 1941 – 2 February 2014) was an English medieval historian.<ref name=Guardianobit>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/mar/06/nicholas-brooks|title=Nicholas Brooks Obituary|author=Nelson, J.|authorlink=Janet Nelson|newspaper=The Guardian|year=2014|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref>

==Biography==
Nicholas Brooks was educated at [[Winchester College]], and graduated from [[Magdalen College, Oxford]], in 1961 with a degree in history.<ref name=Guardianobit /> His doctoral studies on the [[Anglo-Saxon charters]] in the archive of [[Canterbury Cathedral]], also undertaken at Oxford, were supervised by [[Dorothy Whitelock]], and provided the basis for his [[monograph]] ''The Early History of the Church of Canterbury'', published in 1984.<ref name=Guardianobit /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:b7b2bd8b-e2f3-49b2-b6c2-22737329615f |title=The pre-Conquest charters of Christ Church, Canterbury |publisher=Oxford University Research Archive |year=2008 |accessdate=17 February 2017}}</ref> Brooks was lecturer and then senior lecturer in medieval history at the [[University of St Andrews]] from 1964 until 1985, when he was appointed to the chair of medieval history at the [[University of Birmingham]]; in 1989 he was elected as a [[Fellow]] of the [[British Academy]].<ref name=Guardian&BA>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/mar/06/nicholas-brooks|title=Nicholas Brooks Obituary|author=Nelson, J.|newspaper=The Guardian|year=2014|accessdate=24 April 2014|postscript=;}} {{cite web|url=http://www.britac.ac.uk/about/index3.cfm?member=1988|title=British Academy Fellows Record for: BROOKS, Professor Nicholas (14/01/1941-02/02/2014)|author=Committee Structure|publisher=British Academy|year=n.d.|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P50WyBBa?url=http://www.britac.ac.uk/about/index3.cfm?member=1988|archivedate=24 April 2014|deadurl=no|accessdate=24 April 2014|df=}}</ref> From 1991 to 2013 he was chairman of the British Academy's Anglo-Saxon charters project, co-editing the two volumes on the Canterbury archive, published in 2013, with Susan Kelly; he also chaired the British Academy's Stenton Fund Committee, and was a member of the Fabric Advisory Committees for the cathedrals at Canterbury and [[Worcester Cathedral|Worcester]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/mar/06/nicholas-brooks|title=Nicholas Brooks Obituary|author=Nelson, J.|newspaper=The Guardian|year=2014|accessdate=24 April 2014|postscript=;}} {{harvnb|Kelly|2009|loc=Foreword}}; {{cite web|url=http://www.kemble.asnc.cam.ac.uk/node/4|title=Members of the Joint Committee on Anglo-Saxon Charters May 2014|author=Kemble: The Anglo-Saxon Charters Website|publisher=British Academy - Royal Historical Society Joint Committee on Anglo-Saxon Charters|year=n.d.|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PTVFHJzR?url=http://www.kemble.asnc.cam.ac.uk/node/4|archivedate=10 May 2014|deadurl=yes|accessdate=10 May 2014|postscript=;|df=}} {{cite web|url=http://www.britac.ac.uk/about/index3.cfm?committee=1399|title=Stenton Fund Committee Membership|author=Committee Structure|publisher=British Academy|year=n.d.|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P4w6JCW5?url=http://www.britac.ac.uk/about/index3.cfm?committee=1399|archivedate=24 April 2014|deadurl=no|accessdate=24 April 2014|df=}}</ref> After retiring as Professor of Medieval History at the University of Birmingham in 2004, Brooks was an [[Professor#Retired faculty 2|emeritus professor]], in which role he continued to supervise research students.<ref name=Guardian&BA /> A [[festschrift]], ''Myth, Rulership, Church and Charters: Essays in Honour of Nicholas Brooks'', was published in 2008.{{sfn|Gretsch|2009|pp=1136–8}} Until his death, Brooks was also a member of the Research Project Advisory Panel for the study of the 7th- or 8th-century [[Staffordshire Hoard]], which he described as "bling for warrior companions of the king".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staffordshirehoard.org.uk/conservationandresearch/research-project-advisory-panel|title=Research Project Advisory Panel|author=Staffordshire Hoard|publisher=staffordshirehoard.org.uk|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P54L8IEn?url=http://www.staffordshirehoard.org.uk/conservationandresearch/research-project-advisory-panel|archivedate=24 April 2014|deadurl=no|year=2014|accessdate=24 April 2014|postscript=;|df=}} {{cite web|url=http://finds.org.uk/staffshoardsymposium/papers/nicholasbrooks|title=The Staffordshire Hoard and the Mercian Royal Court|author=Nicholas Brooks|publisher=Portable Antiquities Scheme|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P54jj6zQ?url=http://finds.org.uk/staffshoardsymposium/papers/nicholasbrooks|archivedate=24 April 2014|deadurl=no|year=n.d.|accessdate=24 April 2014|df=}}</ref>

==Publications==
As well as "several substantial papers",<ref name=Guardianobit /> Brooks's published works include the following:
* ''Anglo-Saxon Myths: State and Church 400–1066'' (Hambledon, 2000)
* ''Bede and the English'' (Jarrow, 1999)
* ''Charters of Christ Church Canterbury'' (with Susan Kelly, 2 volumes, Oxford University, 2013)
* ''Church, State and Access to Resources in Early Anglo-Saxon England'' (Brixworth, 2003)
* ''Communities and Warfare 700–1400'' (Hambledon, 2000)
* ''The Early History of the Church of Canterbury: Christ Church from 597 to 1066'' (Leicester University, 1984)
* ''Latin and the Vernacular Languages in Early Medieval Britain'' (Leicester University, 1982)
* ''St Oswald of Worcester: Life and Influence'' (with Catherine Cubitt, Leicester University, 1996)
* ''St Wulfstan and his World'' (with [[Julia Barrow]], Ashgate, 2005)

